<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-717-636  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 717 636.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 23 1990 v7 n30 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The FCC's deregulation of ATandamp;T will kill CPE industry. (FederalCommunications Commission, customer premises equipment)(regulatorypolicy) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stearns, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Proposals made in the Federal Communications Commission's (FCC's)Notice of Inquiry, 'Competition in the Interstate InterexchangeMarketplace,' call for the removal of regulations protectingcustomer premises equipment manufacturers.andP;  The FCC claims thatthe regulations were originally instituted because ATandamp;T was thedominant interexchange carrier and could monopolize the market,but believes that situation no longer exists.andP;  However, theassumption that ATandamp;T no longer dominates is erroneous.andP;  Codexmarket research estimates show ATandamp;T in possession of 70 percent ofthe switched market.andP;  Should the proposals pass, the customerpremises equipment industry could disappear completely, faced withoverwhelming competition from integrated carriers.andP;  Since ATandamp;T isthe only vertically integrated carrier it has the potential toprovide most of the components of an integrated network all byitself.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (forecasts).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationCommunications Service SuppliersProposalCustomer Premises EquipmentMarket ShareMonopoliesNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>